On the other hand, as for the hole transfer part, the photocatalytic production of OH radicals is one of the primary mechanisms by which photocatalysts degrade VOCs. The ability of PA/WO3 to produce •OH was tested using a chemical trapping method using DMPO as a spin trap reagent57. After 10 min of blue LED irradiation (460 nm, 2.0 mW/cm2), EPR signals for the •OH-DMPO adduct appeared as shown in Fig. 5e. Note that PA/WO3 produced a prominent signal whereas bare WO3 generated an insignificant one. In general, bare WO3 is not an efficient photocatalyst because of the lower CB edge (~0.4 VNHE)58 that does not provide a sufficient potential to reduce O2 [E0 (O2/O2•−) = −0.33 VNHE and E0 (O2/HO2•) = −0.05 VNHE]13,20. The inability of O2 to scavenge CB electrons in WO3 results in fast recombination and lower photocatalytic activity. After introducing PA, the periodate ions in the in situ formed surface water layer can scavenge CB electrons, which subsequently retards the charge recombination and makes more holes available for the production of •OH that should be the primary oxidant in the PCD process. The photocatalytic oxidation mechanism (see Fig. 5f) can be briefly proposed as follows (Eqs. (1)–(5)):1WO3+hν→hvb++ecb−\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
